        <span id="ctl00_main_lblTitle" class="ArticleHeaderText" style="display:inline-block;">Capturing Laden important to national security: Obama</span>

            <td width="620" valign="top">
             <span id="ctl00_main_lblArticle" class="ArticleText" style="display:inline-block;"><img src="http://www.andhraheadlines.com/\g6\news\me\71811.JPG" hspace="10" vspace="10" align="left"><br>  <p>Washington, Sep 11: US President Barack Obama has said that capturing terror mastermind Osama bin Laden is still extremely important to national security although it won't "solve all the problems".<br><br>Nine years after masterminding the 9/11 attacks and evading the US forces, the Al Qaeda leader has "gone deep underground", but the US will continue to hunt him, Xinhua reported quoting Obama Friday. <br><br>Obama said it remains a high priority to capture or kill bin Laden, and the country's best intelligence officers and special forces are working night and day to make that happen. <br><br>The country will Saturday commemorate the deadly attacks Sep 11, 2001 that took thousands of lives. <br><br>Obama made the remarks during a news conference in the White House. He said extremist groups such as Al Qaeda are still the country's most dangerous enemies. <br><br>Reflecting on the war on terror, Obama expressed regret over the failure to close the Guantanamo Bay prison facility, which he said has been, and still is being, used by Al Qaeda for recruitment purposes. <br><br>"One where we've fallen short is closing Guantanamo. I wanted to close it sooner. We have missed that deadline. It's not for lack of trying. It's because the politics of it are difficult," said the president. <br><br>Obama promised to close the infamous facility in one year after he took office, but the facility still holds over 100 prisoners today.</p><br></span>
